# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: composite-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The binding polymer is often a thermoset resin such as epoxy, but other thermoset or thermoplastic polymers, such as polyester, vinyl ester, or nylon, are sometimes used.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The properties of the final CFRP product can be affected by the type of additives introduced to the binding matrix (resin).
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The most common additive is silica, but other additives such as rubber and carbon nanotubes can be used.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Carbon fiber is sometimes referred to as *graphite-reinforced polymer* or *graphite fiber-reinforced polymer* (*GFRP* is less common, as it clashes with glass-(fiber)-reinforced polymer).
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In this case the composite consists of two parts: a matrix and a reinforcement.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In CFRP the reinforcement is carbon fiber, which provides its strength.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The matrix is usually a thermosetting plastic, such as polyester resin, to bind the reinforcements together.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Because CFRPs consist of two distinct elements, the material properties depend on these two elements.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Reinforcement gives CFRPs their strength and rigidity, measured by stress and elastic modulus respectively.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Unlike isotropic materials like steel and aluminum, CFRPs have directional strength properties.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The properties of a CFRP depend on the layouts of the carbon fiber and the proportion of the carbon fibers relative to the polymer.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The two different equations governing the net elastic modulus of composite materials using the properties of the carbon fibers and the polymer matrix can also be applied to carbon fiber reinforced plastics.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The above equations give an upper and lower bound on the Young's modulus for CFRP and there are many other factors that influence the true value.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Typical epoxy-based CFRPs exhibit virtually no plasticity, with less than 0.5% strain to failure.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Although CFRPs with epoxy have high strength and elastic modulus, the brittle fracture mechanics presents unique challenges to engineers in failure detection since failure occurs catastrophically.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] As such, recent efforts to toughen CFRPs include modifying the existing epoxy material and finding alternative polymer matrix.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] One such material with high promise is PEEK, which exhibits an order of magnitude greater toughness with similar elastic modulus and tensile strength.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] However, PEEK is much more difficult to process and more expensive.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Despite their high initial strength-to-weight ratios, a design limitation of CFRPs are their lack of a definable fatigue limit.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This means, theoretically, that stress cycle failure cannot be ruled out.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Low velocity impacts can make carbon fiber polymers susceptible to damage.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] As a result, when using CFRPs for critical cyclic-loading applications, engineers may need to design in considerable strength safety margins to provide suitable component reliability over its service life.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Environmental effects such as temperature and humidity can have profound effects on the polymer-based composites, including most CFRPs.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] While CFRPs demonstrate excellent corrosion resistance, the effect of moisture at wide ranges of temperatures can lead to degradation of the mechanical properties of CFRPs, particularly at the matrix-fiber interface.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] While the carbon fibers themselves are not affected by the moisture diffusing into the material, the moisture plasticizes the polymer matrix.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This leads to significant changes in properties that are dominantly influenced by the matrix in CFRPs such as compressive, interlaminar shear, and impact properties.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The epoxy matrix used for engine fan blades is designed to be impervious against jet fuel, lubrication, and rain water, and external paint on the composites parts is applied to minimize damage from ultraviolet light.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Carbon fibers can cause galvanic corrosion when CFRP parts are attached to aluminum or mild steel but not to stainless steel or titanium.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs are very hard to machine, and cause significant tool wear.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The tool wear in CFRP machining is dependent on the fiber orientation and machining condition of the cutting process.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] To reduce tool wear various types of coated tools are used in machining CFRP and CFRP-metal stack.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The primary element of CFRPs is a carbon filament; this is produced from a precursor polymer such as polyacrylonitrile (PAN), rayon, or petroleum pitch.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] For synthetic polymers such as PAN or rayon, the precursor is first spun into filament yarns, using chemical and mechanical processes to initially align the polymer chains in a way to enhance the final physical properties of the completed carbon fiber.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Precursor compositions and mechanical processes used during spinning filament yarns may vary among manufacturers.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] After drawing or spinning, the polymer filament yarns are then heated to drive off non-carbon atoms (carbonization), producing the final carbon fiber.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The carbon fibers filament yarns may be further treated to improve handling qualities, then wound onto bobbins.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] From these fibers, a unidirectional sheet is created.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] These sheets are layered onto each other in a quasi-isotropic layup, e.g.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] From the elementary fiber, a bidirectional woven sheet can be created, i.e. a twill with a 2/2 weave.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The process by which most CFRPs are made varies, depending on the piece being created, the finish (outside gloss) required, and how many of the piece will be produced.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In addition, the choice of matrix can have a profound effect on the properties of the finished composite.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Many CFRP parts are created with a single layer of carbon fabric that is backed with fiberglass.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] A tool called a chopper gun is used to quickly create these composite parts.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Once a thin shell is created out of carbon fiber, the chopper gun cuts rolls of fiberglass into short lengths and sprays resin at the same time, so that the fiberglass and resin are mixed on the spot.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The resin is either external mix, wherein the hardener and resin are sprayed separately, or internal mixed, which requires cleaning after every use.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] One method of producing CFRP parts is by layering sheets of carbon fiber cloth into a mold in the shape of the final product.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The alignment and weave of the cloth fibers is chosen to optimize the strength and stiffness properties of the resulting material.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The mold is then filled with epoxy and is heated or air-cured.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The resulting part is very corrosion-resistant, stiff, and strong for its weight.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Parts used in less critical areas are manufactured by draping cloth over a mold, with epoxy either pre-impregnated into the fibers (also known as *pre-preg*) or "painted" over it.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] High-performance parts using single molds are often vacuum-bagged and/or autoclave-cured, because even small air bubbles in the material will reduce strength.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] An alternative to the autoclave method is to use internal pressure via inflatable air bladders or EPS foam inside the non-cured laid-up carbon fiber.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] For simple pieces of which relatively few copies are needed (one or two per day), a vacuum bag can be used.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] A fiberglass, carbon fiber, or aluminum mold is polished and waxed, and has a release agent applied before the fabric and resin are applied, and the vacuum is pulled and set aside to allow the piece to cure (harden).
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] There are three ways to apply the resin to the fabric in a vacuum mold.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The first method is manual and called a wet layup, where the two-part resin is mixed and applied before being laid in the mold and placed in the bag.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The second method is called infusion, where the dry fabric and mold are placed inside the bag while the vacuum pulls the resin through a small tube into the bag, then through a tube with holes or something similar to evenly spread the resin throughout the fabric.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Both of the above methods of applying resin require hand work to spread the resin evenly for a glossy finish with very small pin-holes.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] A third method of constructing composite materials is known as a dry layup.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Here, the carbon fiber material is already impregnated with resin (pre-preg) and is applied to the mold in a similar fashion to adhesive film.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The assembly is then placed in a vacuum to cure.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The dry layup method has the least amount of resin waste and can achieve lighter constructions than wet layup.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Also, because larger amounts of resin are more difficult to bleed out with wet layup methods, pre-preg parts generally have fewer pinholes.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Pinhole elimination with minimal resin amounts generally require the use of autoclave pressures to purge the residual gases out.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] A quicker method uses a compression mold, also commonly known as carbon fiber forging.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This is a two (male and female), or multi-piece mold, usually made out of aluminum or steel and more recently 3D printed plastic.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The mold components are pressed together with the fabric and resin loaded into the inner cavity that ultimately becomes the desired component.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The benefit is the speed of the entire process.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Some car manufacturers, such as BMW, claimed to be able to cycle a new part every 80 seconds.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This technique results in parts with limited or variable strength because the direction of the fibers cannot be controlled as with the other methods.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] For difficult or convoluted shapes, a filament winder can be used to make CFRP parts by winding filaments around a mandrel or a core.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Carbon fiber-reinforced pre-pregs and dry carbon fiber textiles require precise cutting methods to maintain material integrity and reduce defects such as fiber pull-out, delamination and fraying of the cutting edge.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CNC digital cutting systems equipped with drag and oscillating are often used to cut carbon fiber pre-pregs, and rotating knives are commonly used to process carbon fiber fabrics.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Ultrasonic cutting is another method to cut CFRP pre-pregs and is particularly effective in reducing delamination by minimizing mechanical stress during the cutting process.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Waterjet cutting can be the preferred method for thicker and multilayered polymer composites.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The Airbus A350 XWB is 53% CFRP including wing spars and fuselage components, overtaking the Boeing 787 Dreamliner, for the aircraft with the highest weight ratio for CFRP at 50%.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] It was one of the first commercial aircraft to have wing spars made from composites.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The Airbus A380 was one of the first commercial airliners to have a central wing-box made of CFRP and the first with a smoothly contoured wing cross-section instead of partitioning it span-wise into sections.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This flowing, continuous cross section optimises aerodynamic efficiency.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Moreover, the trailing edge, along with the rear bulkhead, empennage, and un-pressurised fuselage are made of CFRP.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] However, delays have pushed order delivery dates back because of manufacturing problems.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Many aircraft that use CFRPs have experienced delays with delivery dates due to the relatively new processes used to make CFRP components, whereas metallic structures are better understood.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] A recurrent problem is the monitoring of structural ageing, for which new methods are required, due to the unusual multi-material and anisotropic nature of CFRPs.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In 1968 a *Hyfil* carbon-fiber fan assembly was in service on the Rolls-Royce Conways of the Vickers VC10s operated by BOAC.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Specialist aircraft designers and manufacturers Scaled Composites have made extensive use of CFRPs throughout their design range, including the first private crewed spacecraft Spaceship One.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs are widely used in micro air vehicles (MAVs) because of their high strength-to-weight ratio.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Airbus then moved to adopt carbon fiber reinforced thermoplastic polymers (CFRTP), because they can be reshaped and reprocessed after forming, can be manufactured faster, has higher impact resistance, is recyclable and remoldable, and has lower processing costs.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs are extensively used in high-end automobile racing.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The high cost of carbon fiber is mitigated by the material's unsurpassed strength-to-weight ratio, and low weight is essential for high-performance automobile racing.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Race-car manufacturers have also developed methods to give carbon fiber pieces strength in a certain direction, making it strong in a load-bearing direction, but weak in directions where little or no load would be placed on the member.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Conversely, manufacturers developed omnidirectional carbon fiber weaves that apply strength in all directions.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This type of carbon fiber assembly is most widely used in the "safety cell" monocoque chassis assembly of high-performance race-cars.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The first carbon fiber monocoque chassis was introduced in Formula One by McLaren in the 1981 season.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] It was designed by John Barnard and was widely copied in the following seasons by other F1 teams due to the extra rigidity provided to the chassis of the cars.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Many supercars over the past few decades have incorporated CFRPs extensively in their manufacture, using it for their monocoque chassis as well as other components.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] As far back as 1971, the Citroën SM offered optional lightweight carbon fiber wheels.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Use of the material has been more readily adopted by low-volume manufacturers who used it primarily for creating body-panels for some of their high-end cars due to its increased strength and decreased weight compared with the glass-reinforced polymer they used for the majority of their products.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs have become a notable material in structural engineering applications.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Studied in an academic context as to their potential benefits in construction, CFRPs have also proved themselves cost-effective in a number of field applications strengthening concrete, masonry, steel, cast iron, and timber structures.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Their use in industry can be either for retrofitting to strengthen an existing structure or as an alternative reinforcing (or prestressing) material instead of steel from the outset of a project.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Retrofitting is popular in many instances as the cost of replacing the deficient structure can greatly exceed the cost of strengthening using CFRP.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Applied to reinforced concrete structures for flexure, the use of CFRPs typically has a large impact on strength (doubling or more the strength of the section is not uncommon), but only moderately increases stiffness (as little as 10%).
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This is because the material used in such applications is typically very strong (e.g., 3 GPa ultimate tensile strength, more than 10 times mild steel) but not particularly stiff (150 to 250 GPa elastic modulus, a little less than steel, is typical).
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] As a consequence, only small cross-sectional areas of the material are used.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Small areas of very high strength but moderate stiffness material will significantly increase strength, but not stiffness.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs can also be used to enhance shear strength of reinforced concrete by wrapping fabrics or fibers around the section to be strengthened.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Wrapping around sections (such as bridge or building columns) can also enhance the ductility of the section, greatly increasing the resistance to collapse under dynamic loading.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Such 'seismic retrofit' is the major application in earthquake-prone areas, since it is much more economic than alternative methods.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] If a column is circular (or nearly so) an increase in axial capacity is also achieved by wrapping.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In this application, the confinement of the CFRP wrap enhances the compressive strength of the concrete.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] However, although large increases are achieved in the ultimate collapse load, the concrete will crack at only slightly enhanced load, meaning that this application is only occasionally used.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Specialist ultra-high modulus CFRP (with tensile modulus of 420 GPa or more) is one of the few practical methods of strengthening cast iron beams.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In typical use, it is bonded to the tensile flange of the section, both increasing the stiffness of the section and lowering the neutral axis, thus greatly reducing the maximum tensile stress in the cast iron.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In the United States, prestressed concrete cylinder pipes (PCCP) account for a vast majority of water transmission mains.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Due to their large diameters, failures of PCCP are usually catastrophic and affect large populations.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Approximately 19,000 miles (31,000 km) of PCCP were installed between 1940 and 2006.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Corrosion in the form of hydrogen embrittlement has been blamed for the gradual deterioration of the prestressing wires in many PCCP lines.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Over the past decade, CFRPs have been used to internally line PCCP, resulting in a fully structural strengthening system.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Inside a PCCP line, the CFRP liner acts as a barrier that controls the level of strain experienced by the steel cylinder in the host pipe.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The composite liner enables the steel cylinder to perform within its elastic range, to ensure the pipeline's long-term performance is maintained.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRP liner designs are based on strain compatibility between the liner and host pipe.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs are more costly materials than commonly used their counterparts in the construction industry, glass fiber-reinforced polymers (GFRPs) and aramid fiber-reinforced polymers (AFRPs), though CFRPs are, in general, regarded as having superior properties.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Much research continues to be done on using CFRPs both for retrofitting and as an alternative to steel as reinforcing or prestressing materials.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Cost remains an issue and long-term durability questions still remain.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Some are concerned about the brittle nature of CFRPs, in contrast to the ductility of steel.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Though design codes have been drawn up by institutions such as the American Concrete Institute, there remains some hesitation among the engineering community about implementing these alternative materials.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In part, this is due to a lack of standardization and the proprietary nature of the fiber and resin combinations on the market.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Carbon fibers are used for fabrication of carbon-fiber microelectrodes.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In this application typically a single carbon fiber with diameter of 5–7 μm is sealed in a glass capillary.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] At the tip the capillary is either sealed with epoxy and polished to make carbon-fiber disk microelectrode or the fiber is cut to a length of 75–150 μm to make carbon-fiber cylinder electrode.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Carbon-fiber microelectrodes are used either in amperometry or fast-scan cyclic voltammetry for detection of biochemical signalling.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs are now widely used in sports equipment such as in squash, tennis, and badminton racquets, sport kite spars, high-quality arrow shafts, hockey sticks, fishing rods, surfboards, high end swim fins, and rowing shells.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Amputee athletes such as Jonnie Peacock use carbon fiber blades for running.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] It is used as a shank plate in some basketball sneakers to keep the foot stable, usually running the length of the shoe just above the sole and left exposed in some areas, usually in the arch.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Controversially, in 2006, cricket bats with a thin carbon-fiber layer on the back were introduced and used in competitive matches by high-profile players including Ricky Ponting and Michael Hussey.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The carbon fiber was claimed to merely increase the durability of the bats, but it was banned from all first-class matches by the ICC in 2007.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] A CFRP bicycle frame weighs less than one of steel, aluminum, or titanium having the same strength.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The type and orientation of the carbon-fiber weave can be designed to maximize stiffness in required directions.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Frames can be tuned to address different riding styles: sprint events require stiffer frames while endurance events may require more flexible frames for rider comfort over longer periods.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The variety of shapes it can be built into has further increased stiffness and also allowed aerodynamic tube sections.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRP forks including suspension fork crowns and steerers, handlebars, seatposts, and crank arms are becoming more common on medium as well as higher-priced bicycles.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRP rims remain expensive but their stability compared to aluminium reduces the need to re-true a wheel and the reduced mass reduces the moment of inertia of the wheel.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRP spokes are rare and most carbon wheelsets retain traditional stainless steel spokes.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs also appear increasingly in other components such as derailleur parts, brake and shifter levers and bodies, cassette sprocket carriers, suspension linkages, disc brake rotors, pedals, shoe soles, and saddle rails.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Although strong and light, impact, over-torquing, or improper installation of CFRP components has resulted in cracking and failures, which may be difficult or impossible to repair.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The fire resistance of polymers and thermo-set composites is significantly improved if a thin layer of carbon fibers is moulded near the surface because a dense, compact layer of carbon fibers efficiently reflects heat.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The key aspect of recycling fiber-reinforced polymers is preserving their mechanical properties while successfully recovering both the thermoplastic matrix and the reinforcing fibers.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CFRPs have a long service lifetime when protected from the sun.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] When it is time to decommission CFRPs, they cannot be melted down in air like many metals.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] When free of vinyl (PVC or polyvinyl chloride) and other halogenated polymers, CFRPs recycling processes can be categorized into four main approaches: mechanical, thermal, chemical, and biological.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Each method offers distinct advantages in terms of material or energy recovery, contributing to sustainability efforts in composite waste management.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The mechanical process primarily involves grinding, which breaks down composite materials into pulverulent charges and fibrous reinforcements.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This method is focused on both the thermoplastic and filler material recovery; however, this process shortens the fibers dramatically.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Just as with downcycled paper, the shortened fibers cause the recycled material to be weaker than the original material.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] There are still many industrial applications that do not need the strength of full-length carbon fiber reinforcement.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] For example, chopped reclaimed carbon fiber can be used in consumer electronics, such as laptops.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] It provides excellent reinforcement of the polymers used even if it lacks the strength-to-weight ratio of an aerospace component.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This method consists in shredding CFRP by pulsed electrical discharges.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Initially developed to extract crystals and precious stones from mining rocks, it is now expected to be developed for composites.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The material is placed in a vessel containing water and two electrodes.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The high voltage electrical pulse generated between the electrodes (50-200 kV) fragments the material into smaller pieces.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The inconvenient of this technique is that the energy consumed is 2.6 times the one of a mechanical route making it not economically competitive in terms of energy saving and needs further investigation.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Thermal processes include several techniques such as incineration, thermolysis, pyrolysis, gasification, fluidized bed processing, and cement plant utilization.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This processes imply the recovery of the fibers by the removal of the resin by volatilizing it, leading to by-products such as gases, liquids or inorganic matter.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This technique consists in exposing the composite to a hot and oxygen-rich flow, in which it is combusted (450–550 °C, 840–1,020 °F) .
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The working temperature is selected in function of the matrix to be decomposed, to limit damages of the fibers.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] After a shredding step to 6-20 mm size, the composite is introduced into a bed of silica sand, on a metallic mesh, in which the resin will be decomposed into oxidized molecules and fiber filaments.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] These components will be carried up with the air stream while heavier particles will sink in the bed.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This last point is a great advantage for contaminated end-of-life products, with painted surfaces, foam cores or metal insert.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] A cyclonic separator enables the recovery of fibers of length ranging between 5 and 10 mm and with very little contamination .
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The matrix is fully oxidized in a second burner operating at approximatively 1,000 °C (1,850 °F) leading to energy recovery and a clean flue gas.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The chemical recycling of CFRPs involves using a reactive solvent at relatively low temperatures (below 350°C) to break down the resin while leaving the fibers intact for reuse.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The solvent degrades the composite matrix into smaller molecular fragments (oligomer), and depending on the chosen solvent system, various processing parameters such as temperature, pressure, and catalysts can be adjusted to optimize the process.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The solvent, often combined with co-solvents or catalysts, penetrates the composite and breaks specific chemical bonds, resulting in recovered monomers from the resin and clean, long fibers with preserved mechanical properties.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The required temperature and pressure depend on the type of resin, with epoxy resins generally needing higher temperatures than polyester resins.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Among the different reactive mediums studied, water is the most commonly used due to its environmental benefits.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] When combined with alkaline catalysts, it effectively degrades many resins, while acidic catalysts are used for more resistant polymers.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Other solvents, such as ethanol, acetone, and their mixtures, have also been explored for this process.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Despite its advantages, this method has some limitations.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] It requires specialized equipment capable of handling corrosive solvents, hazardous chemicals, and high temperatures or pressures, especially when operating under supercritical conditions.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] While extensively researched at the laboratory scale, industrial adoption remains limited, with the technology currently reaching a Technology Readiness Level (TRL) of 4 for carbon fiber recycling.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The dissolution process is a method used to recover both the polymer matrix and fibers from thermoplastic composites without breaking chemical bonds.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Unlike solvolysis, which involves the chemical degradation of the polymer, dissolution simply dissolves the polymer chains into a solvent, allowing for material recovery in its original form.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] An energy analysis of the process indicated that dissolution followed by evaporation was more energy-efficient than precipitation.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Additionally, avoiding precipitation helped minimize polymer loss, improving overall material recovery efficiency.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This method offers a promising approach for sustainable recycling of thermoplastic composites.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] The biological process, though still under development, focuses on biodegradation and composting.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] This method holds promise for bio-based and agro-composites, aiming to create an environmentally friendly end-of-life solution for these materials.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] As research advances, biological recycling may offer an effective means of reducing plastic composite waste in a sustainable manner.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] In 2009, Zyvex Technologies introduced carbon nanotube-reinforced epoxy and carbon pre-pregs.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] Carbon nanotube reinforced polymer (CNRP) is several times stronger and tougher than typical CFRPs and is used in the Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II as a structural material for aircraft.
[src:composite-materials/carbon-fiber-reinforced-polymer] CNRP still uses carbon fiber as the primary reinforcement, but the binding matrix is a carbon nanotube-filled epoxy.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] A **composite** or **composite material** (also **composition material**) is a material which is produced from two or more constituent materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] These constituent materials have notably dissimilar chemical or physical properties and are merged to create a material with properties unlike the individual elements.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Within the finished structure, the individual elements remain separate and distinct, distinguishing composites from mixtures and solid solutions.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composite materials with more than one distinct layer are called *composite laminates*.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composite materials can be less expensive, lighter, stronger or more durable than common materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Some are inspired by biological structures found in plants and animals.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Robotic materials are composites that include sensing, actuation, computation, and communication components.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composite materials are used for construction and technical structures such as boat hulls, swimming pool panels, racing car bodies, shower stalls, bathtubs, storage tanks, imitation granite, and cultured marble sinks and countertops.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] They are also being increasingly used in general automotive applications.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The earliest composite materials were made from straw and mud combined to form bricks for building construction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Ancient brick-making was documented by Egyptian tomb paintings.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Wattle and daub might be the oldest composite materials, at over 6000 years old.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Concrete is the most common artificial composite material of all.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] As of 2009, about 7.5 billion cubic metres of concrete are made each year.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Concrete typically consists of loose stones (construction aggregate) held with a matrix of cement.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Concrete is an inexpensive material resisting large compressive forces, however, susceptible to tensile loading.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] To give concrete the ability to resist being stretched, steel bars, which can resist high stretching (tensile) forces, are often added to concrete to form reinforced concrete.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Fibre-reinforced polymers include carbon-fiber-reinforced polymers and glass-reinforced plastic.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] If classified by matrix then there are thermoplastic composites, short fibre thermoplastics, long fibre thermoplastics or long-fiber-reinforced thermoplastics.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] There are numerous thermoset composites, including paper composite panels.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Many advanced thermoset polymer matrix systems usually incorporate aramid fibre and carbon fibre in an epoxy resin matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Shape-memory polymer composites are high-performance composites, formulated using fibre or fabric reinforcements and shape-memory polymer resin as the matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Since a shape-memory polymer resin is used as the matrix, these composites have the ability to be easily manipulated into various configurations when they are heated above their activation temperatures and will exhibit high strength and stiffness at lower temperatures.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] They can also be reheated and reshaped repeatedly without losing their material properties.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] These composites are ideal for applications such as lightweight, rigid, deployable structures; rapid manufacturing; and dynamic reinforcement.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] High strain composites are another type of high-performance composites that are designed to perform in a high deformation setting and are often used in deployable systems where structural flexing is advantageous.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Although high strain composites exhibit many similarities to shape-memory polymers, their performance is generally dependent on the fibre layout as opposed to the resin content of the matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composites can also use metal fibres reinforcing other metals, as in metal matrix composites (MMC) or ceramic matrix composites (CMC), which includes bone (hydroxyapatite reinforced with collagen fibres), cermet (ceramic and metal), and concrete.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Ceramic matrix composites are built primarily for fracture toughness, not for strength.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Another class of composite materials involve woven fabric composite consisting of longitudinal and transverse laced yarns.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Woven fabric composites are flexible as they are in form of fabric.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Organic matrix/ceramic aggregate composites include asphalt concrete, polymer concrete, mastic asphalt, mastic roller hybrid, dental composite, syntactic foam, and mother of pearl.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Chobham armour is a special type of composite armour used in military applications.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Additionally, thermoplastic composite materials can be formulated with specific metal powders resulting in materials with a density range from 2 g/cm3 to 11 g/cm3 (same density as lead).
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The most common name for this type of material is "high gravity compound" (HGC), although "lead replacement" is also used.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] These materials can be used in place of traditional materials such as aluminium, stainless steel, brass, bronze, copper, lead, and even tungsten in weighting, balancing (for example, modifying the centre of gravity of a tennis racquet), vibration damping, and radiation shielding applications.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] High density composites are an economically viable option when certain materials are deemed hazardous and are banned (such as lead) or when secondary operations costs (such as machining, finishing, or coating) are a factor.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] There have been several studies indicating that interleaving stiff and brittle epoxy-based carbon-fiber-reinforced polymer laminates with flexible thermoplastic laminates can help to make highly toughened composites that show improved impact resistance.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] A sandwich-structured composite is a special class of composite material that is fabricated by attaching two thin but stiff skins to a lightweight but thick core.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The core material is normally low strength material, but its higher thickness provides the sandwich composite with high bending stiffness with overall low density.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Wood is a naturally occurring composite comprising cellulose fibres in a lignin and hemicellulose matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Other engineered laminate composites, such as Mallite, use a central core of end grain balsa wood, bonded to surface skins of light alloy or GRP.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] These generate low-weight, high rigidity materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Particulate composites have particle as filler material dispersed in matrix, which may be nonmetal, such as glass, epoxy.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Automobile tire is an example of particulate composite.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Advanced diamond-like carbon (DLC) coated polymer composites have been reported where the coating increases the surface hydrophobicity, hardness and wear resistance.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Ferromagnetic composites, including those with a polymer matrix consisting, for example, of nanocrystalline filler of Fe-based powders and polymers matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Amorphous and nanocrystalline powders obtained, for example, from metallic glasses can be used.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Their use makes it possible to obtain ferromagnetic nanocomposites with controlled magnetic properties.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Other uses include fishing rods, storage tanks, swimming pool panels, and baseball bats.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The Boeing 787 and Airbus A350 structures including the wings and fuselage are composed largely of composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composite materials are also becoming more common in the realm of orthopedic surgery, and it is the most common hockey stick material.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Carbon composite is a key material in today's launch vehicles and heat shields for the re-entry phase of spacecraft.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] It is widely used in solar panel substrates, antenna reflectors and yokes of spacecraft.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] It is also used in payload adapters, inter-stage structures and heat shields of launch vehicles.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Furthermore, disk brake systems of airplanes and racing cars are using carbon/carbon material, and the composite material with carbon fibres and silicon carbide matrix has been introduced in luxury vehicles and sports cars.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] In 2006, a fibre-reinforced composite pool panel was introduced for in-ground swimming pools, residential as well as commercial, as a non-corrosive alternative to galvanized steel.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] In 2007, an all-composite military Humvee was introduced by TPI Composites Inc and Armor Holdings Inc, the first all-composite military vehicle.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] By using composites the vehicle is lighter, allowing higher payloads.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] In 2008, carbon fibre and DuPont Kevlar (five times stronger than steel) were combined with enhanced thermoset resins to make military transit cases by ECS Composites creating 30-percent lighter cases with high strength.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Pipes and fittings for various purpose like transportation of potable water, fire-fighting, irrigation, seawater, desalinated water, chemical and industrial waste, and sewage are now manufactured in glass reinforced plastics.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composite materials used in tensile structures for facade application provides the advantage of being translucent.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The woven base cloth combined with the appropriate coating allows better light transmission.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] This provides a very comfortable level of illumination compared to the full brightness of outside.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Wind turbine blades, in growing sizes in the order of 50 m length are fabricated in composites since several years.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composites are also used for marine energy structures like tidal turbine blades.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Amputees can run on carbon-fiber composite prosthetic lower legs as fast as non-amputees.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] High-pressure gas cylinders typically about 7–9 litre volume × 300 bar pressure for firemen are nowadays constructed from carbon composite.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Type-4-cylinders include metal only as boss that carries the thread to screw in the valve.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] On 5 September 2019, HMD Global unveiled the Nokia 6.2 and Nokia 7.2 which are claimed to be using polymer composite for the frames.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composite materials are created from individual materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] These individual materials are known as constituent materials, and there are two main categories of it.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] One is the matrix (binder) and the other reinforcement.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] A portion of each kind is needed at least.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The reinforcement receives support from the matrix as the matrix surrounds the reinforcement and maintains its relative positions.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The properties of the matrix are improved as the reinforcements impart their exceptional physical and mechanical properties.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The mechanical properties become unavailable from the individual constituent materials by synergism.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] At the same time, the designer of the product or structure receives options to choose an optimum combination from the variety of matrix and strengthening materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] To shape the engineered composites, it must be formed.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The reinforcement is placed onto the mould surface or into the mould cavity.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Before or after this, the matrix can be introduced to the reinforcement.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The matrix undergoes a melding event which sets the part shape necessarily.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] This melding event can happen in several ways, depending upon the matrix nature, such as solidification from the melted state for a thermoplastic polymer matrix composite or chemical polymerization for a thermoset polymer matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] According to the requirements of end-item design, various methods of moulding can be used.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The natures of the chosen matrix and reinforcement are the key factors influencing the methodology.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The gross quantity of material to be made is another main factor.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] To support high capital investments for rapid and automated manufacturing technology, vast quantities can be used.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Cheaper capital investments but higher labour and tooling expenses at a correspondingly slower rate assists the small production quantities.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Many commercially produced composites use a polymer matrix material often called a resin solution.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] There are many different polymers available depending upon the starting raw ingredients.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] There are several broad categories, each with numerous variations.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The most common are known as polyester, vinyl ester, epoxy, phenolic, polyimide, polyamide, polypropylene, PEEK, and others.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The reinforcement materials are often fibres but also commonly ground minerals.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The various methods described below have been developed to reduce the resin content of the final product, or the fibre content is increased.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] As a rule of thumb, lay up results in a product containing 60% resin and 40% fibre, whereas vacuum infusion gives a final product with 40% resin and 60% fibre content.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The strength of the product is greatly dependent on this ratio.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Martin Hubbe and Lucian A Lucia consider wood to be a natural composite of cellulose fibres in a matrix of lignin.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Several layup designs of composite also involve a co-curing or post-curing of the prepreg with many other media, such as foam or honeycomb.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Generally, this is known as a sandwich structure.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] This is a more general layup for the production of cowlings, doors, radomes or non-structural parts.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Open- and closed-cell-structured foams like polyvinyl chloride, polyurethane, polyethylene, or polystyrene foams, balsa wood, syntactic foams, and honeycombs are generally utilized core materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Open- and closed-cell metal foam can also be utilized as core materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Recently, 3D graphene structures ( also called graphene foam) have also been employed as core structures.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] A recent review by Khurram and Xu et al., have provided the summary of the state-of-the-art techniques for fabrication of the 3D structure of graphene, and the examples of the use of these foam like structures as a core for their respective polymer composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Although the two phases are chemically equivalent, semi-crystalline polymers can be described both quantitatively and qualitatively as composite materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The crystalline portion has a higher elastic modulus and provides reinforcement for the less stiff, amorphous phase.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Polymeric materials can range from 0% to 100% crystallinity aka volume fraction depending on molecular structure and thermal history.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Different processing techniques can be employed to vary the percent crystallinity in these materials and thus the mechanical properties of these materials as described in the physical properties section.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] This effect is seen in a variety of places from industrial plastics like polyethylene shopping bags to spiders which can produce silks with different mechanical properties.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] In many cases these materials act like particle composites with randomly dispersed crystals known as spherulites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] However they can also be engineered to be anisotropic and act more like fiber reinforced composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] In the case of spider silk, the properties of the material can even be dependent on the size of the crystals, independent of the volume fraction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Ironically, single component polymeric materials are some of the most easily tunable composite materials known.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Normally, the fabrication of composite includes wetting, mixing or saturating the reinforcement with the matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The matrix is then induced to bind together (with heat or a chemical reaction) into a rigid structure.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Usually, the operation is done in an open or closed forming mould.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] However, the order and ways of introducing the constituents alters considerably.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Composites fabrication is achieved by a wide variety of methods, including advanced fibre placement (automated fibre placement), fibreglass spray lay-up process, filament winding, lanxide process, tailored fibre placement, tufting, and z-pinning.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The reinforcing and matrix materials are merged, compacted, and cured (processed) within a mould to undergo a melding event.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The part shape is fundamentally set after the melding event.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] However, under particular process conditions, it can deform.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The melding event for a thermoset polymer matrix material is a curing reaction that is caused by the possibility of extra heat or chemical reactivity such as an organic peroxide.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The melding event for a thermoplastic polymeric matrix material is a solidification from the melted state.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The melding event for a metal matrix material such as titanium foil is a fusing at high pressure and a temperature near the melting point.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] It is suitable for many moulding methods to refer to one mould piece as a "lower" mould and another mould piece as an "upper" mould.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Lower and upper does not refer to the mould's configuration in space, but the different faces of the moulded panel.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] There is always a lower mould, and sometimes an upper mould in this convention.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Part construction commences by applying materials to the lower mould.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Lower mould and upper mould are more generalized descriptors than more common and specific terms such as male side, female side, a-side, b-side, tool side, bowl, hat, mandrel, etc.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Continuous manufacturing utilizes a different nomenclature.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Usually, the moulded product is referred to as a panel.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] It can be referred to as casting for certain geometries and material combinations.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] It can be referred to as a profile for certain continuous processes.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Some of the processes are autoclave moulding, vacuum bag moulding, pressure bag moulding, resin transfer moulding, and light resin transfer moulding.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Other types of fabrication include casting, centrifugal casting, braiding (onto a former), continuous casting, filament winding, press moulding, transfer moulding, pultrusion moulding, and slip forming.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] There are also forming capabilities including CNC filament winding, vacuum infusion, wet lay-up, compression moulding, and thermoplastic moulding, to name a few.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The practice of curing ovens and paint booths is also required for some projects.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The composite parts finishing is also crucial in the final design.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Many of these finishes will involve rain-erosion coatings or polyurethane coatings.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The mould and mould inserts are referred to as "tooling".
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The mould/tooling can be built from different materials.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Tooling materials include aluminium, carbon fibre, invar, nickel, reinforced silicone rubber and steel.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Usually, the composite's physical properties are dependent on the direction of consideration, and so are anisotropic.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] This applies to many properties including elastic modulus, ultimate tensile strength, thermal conductivity, and electrical conductivity.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The *rule of mixtures* and *inverse rule of mixtures* give upper and lower bounds for these properties.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The majority of commercial composites are formed with random dispersion and orientation of the strengthening fibres, in which case the composite Young's modulus will fall between the isostrain and isostress bounds.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] However, in applications where the strength-to-weight ratio is engineered to be as high as possible (such as in the aerospace industry), fibre alignment may be tightly controlled.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] In contrast to composites, isotropic materials (for example, aluminium or steel), in standard wrought forms, possess the same stiffness typically despite the directional orientation of the applied forces and/or moments.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] The relationship between forces/moments and strains/curvatures for an isotropic material can be described with the following material properties: Young's Modulus, the shear modulus, and the Poisson's ratio, in relatively simple mathematical relationships.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] For the anisotropic material, it needs the mathematics of a second-order tensor and up to 21 material property constants.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] For the special case of orthogonal isotropy, there are three distinct material property constants for each of Young's Modulus, Shear Modulus and Poisson's ratio—a total of 9 constants to express the relationship between forces/moments and strains/curvatures.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p01] Techniques that take benefit of the materials' anisotropic properties involve mortise and tenon joints (in natural composites such as wood) and pi joints in synthetic composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] In general, particle reinforcement is strengthening the composites less than fiber reinforcement.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] It is used to enhance the stiffness of the composites while increasing the strength and the toughness.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Because of their mechanical properties, they are used in applications in which wear resistance is required.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] For example, hardness of cement can be increased by reinforcing gravel particles, drastically.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Particle reinforcement a highly advantageous method of tuning mechanical properties of materials since it is very easy implement while being low cost.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] where E is the elastic modulus, V is the volume fraction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The subscripts c, p and m are indicating composite, particle and matrix, respectively. $K_{c}$ is a constant can be found empirically.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] where T.S. is the tensile strength, and $K_{s}$ is a constant (not equal to $K_{c}$ ) that can be found empirically.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Short fibers are often cheaper or more convenient to manufacture than longer continuous fibers, but still provide better properties than particle reinforcement.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] A common example is carbon fiber reinforced 3D printing filaments, which use chopped short carbon fibers mixed into a matrix, typically PLA or PETG.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Shear lag theory uses the shear lag model to predict properties such as the Young's modulus for short fiber composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The model assumes that load is transferred from the matrix to the fibers solely through the interfacial shear stresses $\tau _{i}$ acting on the cylindrical interface.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] As *s* becomes larger, this tends towards the rule of mixtures, which represents the Young's modulus parallel to continuous fibers.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] In general, continuous fiber reinforcement is implemented by incorporating a fiber as the strong phase into a weak phase, matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The reason for the popularity of fiber usage is materials with extraordinary strength can be obtained in their fiber form.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Non-metallic fibers are usually showing a very high strength to density ratio compared to metal fibers because of the covalent nature of their bonds.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The most famous example of this is carbon fibers that have many applications extending from sports gear to protective equipment to space industries.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The stress on the composite can be expressed in terms of the volume fraction of the fiber and the matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] where $\sigma$ is the stress, V is the volume fraction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The subscripts c, f and m are indicating composite, fiber and matrix, respectively.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Although the stress–strain behavior of fiber composites can only be determined by testing, there is an expected trend, three stages of the stress–strain curve.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The first stage is the region of the stress–strain curve where both fiber and the matrix are elastically deformed.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] This linearly elastic region can be expressed in the following form.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] where $\sigma$ is the stress, $\epsilon$ is the strain, E is the elastic modulus, and V is the volume fraction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The subscripts c, f, and m are indicating composite, fiber, and matrix, respectively.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] After passing the elastic region for both fiber and the matrix, the second region of the stress–strain curve can be observed.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] In the second region, the fiber is still elastically deformed while the matrix is plastically deformed since the matrix is the weak phase.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The instantaneous modulus can be determined using the slope of the stress–strain curve in the second region.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] To find the modulus in the second region derivative of this equation can be used since the slope of the curve is equal to the modulus.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] In most cases it can be assumed $E_{c}'=V_{f}E_{f}$ since the second term is much less than the first one.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] In reality, the derivative of stress with respect to strain is not always returning the modulus because of the binding interaction between the fiber and matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The strength of the interaction between these two phases can result in changes in the mechanical properties of the composite.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The compatibility of the fiber and matrix is a measure of internal stress.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The covalently bonded high strength fibers (e.g. carbon fibers) experience mostly elastic deformation before the fracture since the plastic deformation can happen due to dislocation motion.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Whereas, metallic fibers have more space to plastically deform, so their composites exhibit a third stage where both fiber and the matrix are plastically deforming.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Metallic fibers have many applications to work at cryogenic temperatures that is one of the advantages of composites with metal fibers over nonmetallic.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The subscripts c, f, and m are indicating composite, fiber, and matrix, respectively. $\sigma _{f}(\epsilon _{c})$ and $\sigma _{m}(\epsilon _{c})$ are for fiber and matrix flow stresses respectively.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Just after the third region the composite exhibit necking.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The necking strain of composite is happened to be between the necking strain of the fiber and the matrix just like other mechanical properties of the composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The necking strain of the weak phase is delayed by the strong phase.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The amount of the delay depends upon the volume fraction of the strong phase.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Thus, the tensile strength of the composite can be expressed in terms of the volume fraction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] where T.S. is the tensile strength, $\sigma$ is the stress, $\epsilon$ is the strain, E is the elastic modulus, and V is the volume fraction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Evidently, the composite tensile strength can be higher than the matrix if $(T.S.)_{c}$ is greater than $(T.S.)_{m}$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Although this minimum value is very low in practice, it is very important to know since the reason for the incorporation of continuous fibers is to improve the mechanical properties of the materials/composites, and this value of volume fraction is the threshold of this improvement.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] A change in the angle between the applied stress and fiber orientation will affect the mechanical properties of fiber-reinforced composites, especially the tensile strength.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] This angle, $\theta$ , can be used predict the dominant tensile fracture mechanism.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] At small angles, $\theta \approx 0^{\circ }$ , the dominant fracture mechanism is the same as with load-fiber alignment, tensile fracture.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The resolved force acting upon the length of the fibers is reduced by a factor of $\cos \theta$ from rotation. $F_{\mbox{res}}=F\cos \theta$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The resolved area on which the fiber experiences the force is increased by a factor of $\cos \theta$ from rotation. $A_{\mbox{res}}=A_{0}/\cos \theta$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Taking the effective tensile strength to be $({\mbox{T.S.}})_{\mbox{c}}=F_{\mbox{res}}/A_{\mbox{res}}$ and the aligned tensile strength $\sigma _{\parallel }^{*}=F/A$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] At moderate angles, $\theta \approx 45^{\circ }$ , the material experiences shear failure.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The effective force direction is reduced with respect to the aligned direction. $F_{\mbox{res}}=F\cos \theta$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The resolved area on which the force acts is $A_{\mbox{res}}=A_{m}/\sin \theta$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The resulting tensile strength depends on the shear strength of the matrix, $\tau _{m}$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] At extreme angles, $\theta \approx 90^{\circ }$ , the dominant mode of failure is tensile fracture in the matrix in the perpendicular direction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] As in the isostress case of layered composite materials, the strength in this direction is lower than in the aligned direction.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The effective areas and forces act perpendicular to the aligned direction so they both scale by $\sin \theta$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The resolved tensile strength is proportional to the transverse strength, $\sigma _{\perp }^{*}$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] where $\theta _{c_{1}}$ is the critical angle between longitudinal fracture and shear failure, and $\theta _{c_{2}}$ is the critical angle between shear failure and transverse fracture.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] By ignoring length effects, this model is most accurate for continuous fibers and does not effectively capture the strength-orientation relationship for short fiber reinforced composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Furthermore, most realistic systems do not experience the local maxima predicted at the critical angles.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The Tsai-Hill criterion provides a more complete description of fiber composite tensile strength as a function of orientation angle by coupling the contributing yield stresses: $\sigma _{\parallel }^{*}$ , $\sigma _{\perp }^{*}$ , and $\tau _{m}$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Anisotropy in the tensile strength of fiber reinforced composites can be removed by randomly orienting the fiber directions within the material.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] It sacrifices the ultimate strength in the aligned direction for an overall, isotropically strengthened material.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Where K is an empirically determined reinforcement factor; similar to the particle reinforcement equation.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] For fibers with randomly distributed orientations in a plane, $K\approx 0.38$ , and for a random distribution in 3D, $K\approx 0.20$ .
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Composite materials are generally anisotropic, and in many cases are orthotropic.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] When considering each ply individually, it is assumed that they can be treated as thi lamina and so out–of–plane stresses and strains are negligible.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] For fiber-reinforced composite, the fiber orientation in material affect anisotropic properties of the structure.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] From characterizing technique i.e. tensile testing, the material properties were measured based on sample (1-2) coordinate system.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The tensors above express stress-strain relationship in (1-2) coordinate system.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] While the known material properties is in the principal coordinate system (x-y) of material.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Transforming the tensor between two coordinate system help identify the material properties of the tested sample.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The most common types of fibers used in industry are glass fibers, carbon fibers, and kevlar due to their ease of production and availability.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Their mechanical properties are very important to know, therefore the table of their mechanical properties is given below to compare them with S97 steel.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The angle of fiber orientation is very important because of the anisotropy of fiber composites (please see the section "Physical properties" for a more detailed explanation).
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The mechanical properties of the composites can be tested using standard mechanical testing methods by positioning the samples at various angles (the standard angles are 0°, 45°, and 90°) with respect to the orientation of fibers within the composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] In general, 0° axial alignment makes composites resistant to longitudinal bending and axial tension/compression, 90° hoop alignment is used to obtain resistance to internal/external pressure, and ± 45° is the ideal choice to obtain resistance against pure torsion.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Although strength and stiffness of steel and aluminum alloys are comparable to fiber composites, specific strength and stiffness of composites (i.e. in relation to their weight) are significantly higher.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Shock, impact of varying speed, or repeated cyclic stresses can provoke the laminate to separate at the interface between two layers, a condition known as delamination.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Individual fibres can separate from the matrix, for example, fibre pull-out.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Composites can fail on the macroscopic or microscopic scale.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Compression failures can happen at both the macro scale or at each individual reinforcing fibre in compression buckling.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Tension failures can be net section failures of the part or degradation of the composite at a microscopic scale where one or more of the layers in the composite fail in tension of the matrix or failure of the bond between the matrix and fibres.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Some composites are brittle and possess little reserve strength beyond the initial onset of failure while others may have large deformations and have reserve energy absorbing capacity past the onset of damage.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The distinctions in fibres and matrices that are available and the mixtures that can be made with blends leave a very broad range of properties that can be designed into a composite structure.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] The most famous failure of a brittle ceramic matrix composite occurred when the carbon-carbon composite tile on the leading edge of the wing of the Space Shuttle Columbia fractured when impacted during take-off.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] It directed to the catastrophic break-up of the vehicle when it re-entered the Earth's atmosphere on 1 February 2003.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Composites have relatively poor bearing strength compared to metals.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Another failure mode is fiber tensile fracture, which becomes more likely when fibers are aligned with the loading direction, so is the possibility of fiber tensile fracture, assuming the tensile strength exceeds that of the matrix.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] When a fiber has some angle of misorientation θ, several fracture modes are possible.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Intermediate angles of misorientation θ lead to matrix shear failure.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Again the cross sectional area is modified but since shear stress is now the driving force for failure the area of the matrix parallel to the fibers is of interest, increasing by a factor of 1/sin θ.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Similarly, the force parallel to this area again decreases (*F/*cos θ) leading to a total tensile strength of *τmy /*sin θ cos θ where *τmy* is the matrix shear strength.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Finally, for large values of θ (near π/2) transverse matrix failure is the most likely to occur, since the fibers no longer carry the majority of the load.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Composites are tested before and after construction to assist in predicting and preventing failures.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Pre-construction testing may adopt finite element analysis (FEA) for ply-by-ply analysis of curved surfaces and predicting wrinkling, crimping and dimpling of composites.
[src:composite-materials/composite-material-p02] Materials may be tested during manufacturing and after construction by various non-destructive methods including ultrasonic, thermography, shearography and X-ray radiography, and laser bond inspection for NDT of relative bond strength integrity in a localized area.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] FRPs are commonly used in the aerospace, automotive, marine, and construction industries.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] They are commonly found in ballistic armour and cylinders for self-contained breathing apparatuses.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Bakelite was the first fibre-reinforced plastic.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Leo Baekeland had originally set out to find a replacement for shellac (made from the excretion of lac bugs).
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Chemists had begun to recognise that many natural resins and fibres were polymers, and Baekeland investigated the reactions of phenol and formaldehyde.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] He first produced a soluble phenol-formaldehyde shellac called "Novolak" that never became a market success, then turned to developing a binder for asbestos which, at that time, was moulded with rubber.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] By controlling the pressure and temperature applied to phenol and formaldehyde, he found in 1905 he could produce his dreamed of hard mouldable material (the world's first synthetic plastic): bakelite.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] He announced his invention at a meeting of the American Chemical Society on 5 February 1909.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The development of fibre-reinforced plastic for commercial use was being extensively researched in the 1930s.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In the United Kingdom, considerable research was undertaken by pioneers such as Norman de Bruyne.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] It was particularly of interest to the aviation industry.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Mass production of glass strands was discovered in 1932, when Games Slayter, a researcher at Owens-Illinois accidentally directed a jet of compressed air at a stream of molten glass and produced fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A patent for this method of producing glass wool was first applied for in 1933.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Owens joined with the Corning company in 1935 and the method was adapted by Owens Corning to produce its patented "fibreglas" (one "s") in 1936.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Originally, fibreglas was a glass wool with fibres entrapping a great deal of gas, making it useful as an insulator, especially at high temperatures.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A suitable resin for combining the "fibreglas" with a plastic to produce a composite material, was developed in 1936 by du Pont.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The first ancestor of modern polyester resins is Cyanamid's resin of 1942.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Peroxide curing systems were used by then.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] With the combination of fibreglas and resin the gas content of the material was replaced by plastic.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This reduced the insulation properties to values typical of the plastic, but now for the first time the composite showed great strength and promise as a structural and building material.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Confusingly, many glass fibre composites continued to be called "fibreglass" (as a generic name) and the name was also used for the low-density glass wool product containing gas instead of plastic.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Ray Greene of Owens Corning is credited with producing the first composite boat in 1937, but did not proceed further at the time due to the brittle nature of the plastic used.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In 1939, Russia was reported to have constructed a passenger boat of plastic materials, and the United States a fuselage and wings of an aircraft.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The first car to have a fibre-glass body was the 1946 Stout Scarab.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The Ford prototype of 1941 could have been the first plastic car, but there is some uncertainty around the materials used as it was destroyed shortly afterwards.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The first fibre-reinforced plastic plane was either the Fairchild F-46, first flown on 12 May 1937, or the Californian built Bennett Plastic Plane.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A fibreglass fuselage was used on a modified Vultee BT-13A designated the XBT-16 based at Wright Field in late 1942.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In 1943, further experiments were undertaken building structural aircraft parts from composite materials resulting in the first plane, a Vultee BT-15, with a GFRP fuselage, designated the XBT-19, being flown in 1944.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A significant development in the tooling for GFRP components had been made by Republic Aviation Corporation in 1943.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Carbon fibre production began in the late 1950s and was used, though not widely in British industry until the early 1960s.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Aramid fibres were being produced around this time also, appearing first under the trade name Nomex by DuPont.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Today, each of these fibres is used widely in industry for any applications that require plastics with specific strength or elastic qualities.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Glass fibres are the most common across all industries, although carbon-fibre and carbon-fibre-aramid composites are widely found in aerospace, automotive and sporting good applications.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] These three (glass, carbon, and aramid) continue to be the important categories of fibre used in FRP.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Global polymer production on the scale present today began in the mid 20th century, when low material and productions costs, new production technologies and new product categories, combined to make polymer production economical.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The industry finally matured in the late 1970s, when world polymer production surpassed that of steel, making polymers the ubiquitous material that they are today.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre-reinforced plastics have been a significant aspect of this industry from the beginning.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A polymer is generally manufactured by step-growth polymerisation or addition polymerisation.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] When one or more polymers are combined with various agents to enhance or in any way alter their material properties, the result is referred to as a plastic.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Composite plastics refers to those types of plastics that result from bonding two or more homogeneous materials with different material properties to derive a final product with certain desired material and mechanical properties.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre-reinforced plastics are a category of composite plastics that specifically use fibre materials to mechanically enhance the strength and elasticity of plastics.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The original plastic material without fibre reinforcement is known as the matrix or binding agent.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The matrix is a tough but relatively weak plastic that is reinforced by stronger stiffer reinforcing filaments or fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The extent that strength and elasticity are enhanced in a fibre-reinforced plastic depends on the mechanical properties of both the fibre and matrix, their volume relative to one another, and the fibre length and orientation within the matrix.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Reinforcement of the matrix occurs by definition when the FRP material exhibits increased strength or elasticity relative to the strength and elasticity of the matrix alone.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] FRP involves two distinct processes, the first is the process whereby the fibrous material is manufactured and formed, the second is the process whereby fibrous materials are bonded with the matrix during moulding.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Three-dimensional fibreglass-reinforced polymer composites are materials with three-dimensional fibre structures that incorporate fibres in the x-direction, y-direction and z-direction.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The development of three-dimensional orientations arose from industry's need to reduce fabrication costs, to increase through-thickness mechanical properties, and to improve impact damage tolerance; all were problems associated with two-dimensional fibre-reinforced polymers.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre preforms are how the fibres are manufactured before being bonded to the matrix.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre preforms are often manufactured in sheets, continuous mats, or as continuous filaments for spray applications.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The four major ways to manufacture the fibre preform is through the textile processing techniques of weaving, knitting, braiding and stitching.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The second major way of manufacturing fibre preforms is Braiding.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Braiding is suited to the manufacture of narrow width flat or tubular fabric and is not as capable as weaving in the production of large volumes of wide fabrics.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Braiding is done over top of mandrels that vary in cross-sectional shape or dimension along their length.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Braiding is limited to objects about a brick in size.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Unlike standard weaving, braiding can produce fabric that contains fibres at 45-degree angles to one another.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Braiding three-dimensional fibres can be done using four-step, two-step or Multilayer Interlock Braiding.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Four-step or row and column braiding utilises a flat bed containing rows and columns of yarn carriers that form the shape of the desired preform.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Additional carriers are added to the outside of the array, the precise location and quantity of which depends upon the exact preform shape and structure required.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] There are four separate sequences of row and column motion, which act to interlock the yarns and produce the braided preform.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The yarns are mechanically forced into the structure between each step to consolidate the structure, as a reed is used in weaving.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Two-step braiding is unlike the four-step process because the two-step process includes a large number of yarns fixed in the axial direction and a lesser number of braiding yarns.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The process consists of two steps in which the braiding carriers move completely through the structure between the axial carriers.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This relatively simple sequence of motions is capable of forming preforms of essentially any shape, including circular and hollow shapes.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Unlike the four-step process, the two-step process does not require mechanical compaction: the motions involved in the process allows the braid to be pulled tight by yarn tension alone.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The last type of braiding is multi-layer interlocking braiding that consists of a number of standard circular braiders being joined to form a cylindrical braiding frame.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This frame has a number of parallel braiding tracks around the circumference of the cylinder but the mechanism allows the transfer of yarn carriers between adjacent tracks forming a multilayer braided fabric with yarns interlocking to adjacent layers.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The multilayer interlock braid differs from both the four-step and two-step braids in that the interlocking yarns are primarily in the plane of the structure and thus do not significantly reduce the in-plane properties of the preform.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The four-step and two-step processes produce a greater degree of interlinking as the braiding yarns travel through the thickness of the preform, but therefore contribute less to the in-plane performance of the preform.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A disadvantage of the multilayer interlock equipment is that due to the conventional sinusoidal movement of the yarn carriers to form the preform, the equipment is not able to have the density of yarn carriers that is possible with the two-step and four-step machines.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Stitching is arguably the simplest of the four main textile manufacturing techniques and one that can be performed with the smallest investment in specialised machinery.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Basically stitching consists of inserting a needle, carrying the stitch thread, through a stack of fabric layers to form a 3D structure.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The advantages of stitching are that it is possible to stitch both dry and prepreg fabric, although the tackiness of the prepreg makes the process difficult and generally creates more damage within the prepreg material than in the dry fabric.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Stitching also utilises the standard two-dimensional fabrics that are commonly in use within the composite industry, so there is a sense of familiarity with the material systems.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The use of standard fabric also allows a greater degree of flexibility in the fabric lay-up of the component than is possible with the other textile processes, which have restrictions on the fibre orientations that can be produced.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A rigid structure is usually used to establish the shape of FRP components.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Parts can be laid up on a flat surface referred to as a "caul plate" or on a cylindrical structure referred to as a "mandrel".
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] However, most fibre-reinforced plastic parts are created with a mould or "tool".
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Moulds can be concave female moulds, male moulds, or the mould can completely enclose the part with a top and bottom mould.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The moulding processes of FRP plastics begins by placing the fibre preform on or in the mould.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The fibre preform can be dry fibre, or fibre that already contains a measured amount of resin called "prepreg".
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Dry fibres are "wetted" with resin either by hand or the resin is injected into a closed mould.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The part is then cured, leaving the matrix and fibres in the shape created by the mould.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Heat and/or pressure are sometimes used to cure the resin and improve the quality of the final part.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The different methods of forming are listed below.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Individual sheets of prepreg material are laid up and placed in a female-style mould along with a balloon-like bladder.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The mould is closed and placed in a heated press.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Finally, the bladder is pressurised forcing the layers of material against the mould walls.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] When the raw material (plastic block, rubber block, plastic sheet, or granules) contains reinforcing fibres, a compression moulded part qualifies as a fibre-reinforced plastic.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] More typically the plastic preform used in compression moulding does not contain reinforcing fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In compression moulding, a "preform" or "charge", of SMC, BMC is placed into mould cavity.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The mould is closed and the material is formed and cured inside by pressure and heat.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Compression moulding offers excellent detailing for geometric shapes ranging from pattern and relief detailing to complex curves and creative forms, to precision engineering all within a maximum curing time of 20 minutes.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Individual sheets of prepreg material are laid-up and placed in an open mould.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The material is covered with release film, bleeder/breather material and a vacuum bag.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A vacuum is pulled on part and the entire mould is placed into an autoclave (heated pressure vessel).
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The part is cured with a continuous vacuum to extract entrapped gasses from laminate.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This is a very common process in the aerospace industry because it affords precise control over moulding due to a long, slow cure cycle that is anywhere from one to several hours.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This precise control creates the exact laminate geometric forms needed to ensure strength and safety in the aerospace industry, but it is also slow and labour-intensive, meaning costs often confine it to the aerospace industry.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Sheets of prepreg material are wrapped around a steel or aluminium mandrel.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The prepreg material is compacted by nylon or polypropylene cello tape.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Parts are typically batch cured by vacuum bagging and hanging in an oven.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] After cure, the cello and mandrel are removed leaving a hollow carbon tube.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This process creates strong and robust hollow carbon tubes.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Wet layup forming combines fibre reinforcement and the matrix as they are placed on the forming tool.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Reinforcing fibre layers are placed in an open mould and then saturated with a wet resin by pouring it over the fabric and working it into the fabric.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The mould is then left so that the resin will cure, usually at room temperature, though heat is sometimes used to ensure a proper cure.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Sometimes a vacuum bag is used to compress a wet layup.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Glass fibres are most commonly used for this process, the results are widely known as fibreglass, and is used to make common products like skis, canoes, kayaks and surf boards.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Continuous strands of fibreglass are pushed through a hand-held gun that both chops the strands and combines them with a catalysed resin such as polyester.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The impregnated chopped glass is shot onto the mould surface in whatever thickness and design the human operator thinks is appropriate.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This process is good for large production runs at economical cost, but produces geometric shapes with less strength than other moulding processes and has poor dimensional tolerance.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Machines pull fibre bundles through a wet bath of resin and wound over a rotating steel mandrel in specific orientations.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Parts are cured either room temperature or elevated temperatures.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Mandrel is extracted, leaving a final geometric shape but can be left in some cases.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre bundles and slit fabrics are pulled through a wet bath of resin and formed into the rough part shape.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Saturated material is extruded from a heated closed die curing while being continuously pulled through die.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Some of the end products of pultrusion are structural shapes, i.e.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] These materials can be used to create all sorts of fibreglass structures such as ladders, platforms, handrails, pipes, and pump supports.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fabrics are placed into a mould into which wet resin is then injected.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Resin is typically pressurised and forced into a cavity which is under vacuum in resin transfer moulding.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Resin is entirely pulled into cavity under vacuum in vacuum-assisted resin transfer moulding.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This moulding process allows precise tolerances and detailed shaping, but can sometimes fail to fully saturate the fabric leading to weak spots in the final shape.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] FRP allows the alignment of the glass fibres of thermoplastics to suit specific design programs.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Specifying the orientation of reinforcing fibres can increase the strength and resistance to deformation of the polymer.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Glass reinforced polymers are strongest and most resistive to deforming forces when the polymers fibres are parallel to the force being exerted, and are weakest when the fibres are perpendicular.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This alignment significantly enhances the tensile strength of the material along the fibre direction, making it ideal for load-bearing applications where directional strength is critical.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Thus, this ability is at once both an advantage or a limitation depending on the context of use.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Weak spots of perpendicular fibres can be used for natural hinges and connections, but can also lead to material failure when production processes fail to properly orient the fibres parallel to expected forces.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] When forces are exerted perpendicular to the orientation of fibres, the strength and elasticity of the polymer is less than the matrix alone.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In cast resin components made of glass reinforced polymers such as UP and EP, the orientation of fibres can be oriented in two-dimensional and three-dimensional weaves.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This means that when forces are possibly perpendicular to one orientation, they are parallel to another orientation; this eliminates the potential for weak spots in the polymer.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The type of load and its orientation with respect to the fibres affect what failure mechanisms are favoured.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The sequence of failure initiation in composite laminates is highly variable, depending on the specific material system and the applied loading conditions.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Damage growth can be initiated by either matrix-dominated or fibre-dominated failure mechanisms.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] However, the interface between layers often serves as a weak link; delamination is a common failure mode because interlaminar strength is typically the lowest in a laminated material, suggesting the interface is frequently the first to fail.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Observed sequences of failure initiation provide further insight.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Generally, the initial deterioration of composites under repeated loading often appears as a gradual loss of stiffness, which is attributed to failure or breakdown within the resin.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In adhesive joints, fracture can begin as debonding at the adhesive/adherend interface, fibre peel-off from the outermost lamina, or intra- or inter-laminar debonding within the composite adherends.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] It is notable that the relationship between resistance change and debonded area in these joints may not be unique when various micromechanisms are competing.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Under tensile loading in microvascular composites, fibre damage in the 0° layers can initiate first, followed by resin damage in the 90° layers.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In carbon-fibre reinforced polymer laminated plates subjected to tensile loading, the typical sequence observed is matrix tensile damage and microcrack formation in 90° plies, which then leads to delamination between plies, and ultimately, tensile failure of fibres in 0° plies.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Furthermore, ply cracking, where transverse stresses exceed the ply's capacity, can sometimes trigger subsequent delamination.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A broken fibre can also initiate a transverse crack, which then contributes to reducing the overall transverse strength of the material.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A thermoset polymer matrix material, or engineering grade thermoplastic polymer matrix material, must meet certain requirements in order to first be suitable for FRPs and ensure a successful reinforcement of itself.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The matrix must be able to properly saturate, and preferably bond chemically with the fibre reinforcement for maximum adhesion within a suitable curing period.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The matrix must also completely envelop the fibres to protect them from cuts and notches that would reduce their strength, and to transfer forces to the fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The fibres must also be kept separate from each other so that if failure occurs it is localised as much as possible, and if failure occurs the matrix must also debond from the fibre for similar reasons.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Finally, the matrix should be of a plastic that remains chemically and physically stable during and after the reinforcement and moulding processes.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] "Fibreglass reinforced plastics" or FRPs (commonly referred to simply as fibreglass) use textile grade glass fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] These textile fibres are different from other forms of glass fibres used to deliberately trap air, for insulating applications (see glass wool).
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Textile glass fibres begin as varying combinations of SiO2, Al2O3, B2O3, CaO, or MgO in powder form.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] These mixtures are then heated through direct melting to temperatures around 1300 degrees Celsius, after which dies are used to extrude filaments of glass fibre in diameter ranging from 9 to 17 μm.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] These filaments are then wound into larger threads and spun onto bobbins for transportation and further processing.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Glass fibre is by far the most popular means to reinforce plastic and thus enjoys a wealth of production processes, some of which are applicable to aramid and carbon fibres as well owing to their shared fibrous qualities.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Roving is a process where filaments are spun into larger diameter threads.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] These threads are then commonly used for woven reinforcing glass fabrics and mats, and in spray applications.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre fabrics (glass cloth, etc.) are web-form fabric reinforcing material that has both warp and weft directions.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre mats are web-form non-woven mats of glass fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Mats are manufactured in cut dimensions with chopped fibres, or in continuous mats using continuous fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Chopped fibre glass is used in processes where lengths of glass threads are cut between 3 and 26 mm, threads are then used in plastics most commonly intended for moulding processes.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Glass fibre short strands are short 0.2–0.3 mm strands of glass fibres that are used to reinforce thermoplastics most commonly for injection moulding.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Carbon fibres are created when polyacrylonitrile fibres (PAN), Pitch resins, or Rayon are carbonised (through oxidation and thermal pyrolysis) at high temperatures.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Through further processes of graphitising or stretching, the fibres strength or elasticity can be enhanced respectively.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Carbon fibres are manufactured in diameters analogous to glass fibres with diameters ranging from 4 to 17 μm.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] These fibres wound into larger threads for transportation and further production processes.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Further production processes include weaving or braiding into carbon fabrics, cloths and mats analogous to those described for glass that can then be used in actual reinforcements.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Aramid fibres are most commonly known as Kevlar, Nomex and Technora.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Aramids are generally prepared by the reaction between an amine group and a carboxylic acid halide group (aramid);.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Commonly, this occurs when an aromatic polyamide is spun from a liquid concentration of sulphuric acid into a crystallised fibre.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibres are then spun into larger threads in order to weave into large ropes or woven fabrics (aramid).
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Aramid fibres are manufactured with varying grades based on strength and rigidity, so that the material can be adapted to meet specific design requirements, such as cutting the tough material during manufacture.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre-reinforced plastics are best suited for any design program that demands weight savings, precision engineering, definite tolerances, and the simplification of parts in both production and operation.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The fibres provide strength and stiffness to the material, while the polymer matrix holds the fibres together and transfers loads between them.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] FRP composites have a wide range of applications across various industries due to their unique combination of properties, including high strength-to-weight ratio, corrosion resistance, and design flexibility.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] A moulded polymer product is cheaper, faster, and easier to manufacture than a cast aluminium or steel product, and maintains similar and sometimes better tolerances and material strengths.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Engine intake manifolds are made from glass-fibre-reinforced PA 66.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Aluminium windows, doors and façades are thermally insulated by using thermal insulation plastics made of glass fibre reinforced polyamide.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In 1977 Ensinger GmbH produced first insulation profile for window systems.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] FRP can be applied to strengthen the beams, columns, and slabs of buildings and bridges.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] It is possible to increase the strength of structural members even after they have been severely damaged due to loading conditions.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In the case of damaged reinforced concrete members, this would first require the repair of the member by removing loose debris and filling in cavities and cracks with mortar or epoxy resin.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Once the member is repaired, strengthening can be achieved through wet, hand lay-up of fibre sheets impregnated with epoxy resin, applied to the cleaned and prepared surfaces of the member.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Two techniques are typically adopted for the strengthening of beams, depending on the strength enhancement desired: flexural strengthening or shear strengthening.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In many cases it may be necessary to provide both strength enhancements.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] For the flexural strengthening of a beam, FRP sheets or plates are applied to the tension face of the member (the bottom face for a simply supported member with applied top loading or gravity loading).
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Principal tensile fibres are oriented parallel to the beam's longitudinal axis, similar to its internal flexural steel reinforcement.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This increases the beam strength and its stiffness (load required to cause unit deflection), but decreases the deflection capacity and ductility.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] For the shear strengthening of a beam, the FRP is applied on the web (sides) of a member with fibres oriented transverse to the beam's longitudinal axis.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Resisting of shear forces is achieved in a similar manner as internal steel stirrups, by bridging shear cracks that form under applied loading.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] FRP can be applied in several configurations, depending on the exposed faces of the member and the degree of strengthening desired, this includes: side bonding, U-wraps (U-jackets), and closed wraps (complete wraps).
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Side bonding involves applying FRP to the sides of the beam only.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] It provides the least amount of shear strengthening due to failures caused by de-bonding from the concrete surface at the FRP free edges.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] For U-wraps, the FRP is applied continuously in a 'U' shape around the sides and bottom (tension) face of the beam.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] If all faces of a beam are accessible, the use of closed wraps is desirable as they provide the most strength enhancement.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Closed wrapping involves applying FRP around the entire perimeter of the member, such that there are no free ends and the typical failure mode is rupture of the fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] For all wrap configurations, the FRP can be applied along the length of the member as a continuous sheet or as discrete strips, having a predefined minimum width and spacing.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Slabs may be strengthened by applying FRP strips at their bottom (tension) face.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This will result in better flexural performance, since the tensile resistance of the slabs is supplemented by the tensile strength of FRP.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In the case of beams and slabs, the effectiveness of FRP strengthening depends on the performance of the resin chosen for bonding.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This is particularly an issue for shear strengthening using side bonding or U-wraps.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Columns are typically wrapped with FRP around their perimeter, as with closed or complete wrapping.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] This not only results in higher shear resistance, but more crucial for column design, it results in increased compressive strength under axial loading.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The FRP wrap works by restraining the lateral expansion of the column, which can enhance confinement in a similar manner as spiral reinforcement does for the column core.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In June 2013, KONE elevator company announced Ultrarope for use as a replacement for steel cables in elevators.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] It seals the carbon fibres in high-friction polymer.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Unlike steel cable, Ultrarope was designed for buildings that require up to 1,000 m (3,300 ft) of lift.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Steel elevators top out at 500 m (1,600 ft).
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The company estimated that in a 500 m (1,600 ft) high building, an elevator would use 15% less electrical power than a steel-cabled version.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] As of June 2013, the product had passed all European Union and United States certification tests.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] FRP is used in designs that require a measure of strength or modulus of elasticity for which non-reinforced plastics and other material choices are ill-suited, either mechanically or economically.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The primary design consideration for using FRP is to ensure that the material is used economically and in a manner that takes advantage of its specific structural characteristics, but this is not always the case.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The orientation of fibres creates a material weakness perpendicular to the fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Thus the use of fibre reinforcement and their orientation affects the strength, rigidity, elasticity and hence the functionality of the final product itself.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Orienting the fibres either unidirectionally, 2-dimensionally, or 3-dimensionally during production affects the strength, flexibility, and elasticity of the final product.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Orienting the fibres in more dimensions avoids this either-or scenario and creates objects that seek to avoid any specific weakness due to the unidirectional orientation of fibres.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] The properties of strength, flexibility and elasticity can also be magnified or diminished through the geometric shape and design of the final product.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] For example, ensuring proper wall thickness and creating multifunctional geometric shapes that can be moulded as a single piece enhances the material and structural integrity of the product by reducing the requirements for joints, connections, and hardware.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] As a subset of plastic, FR plastics are liable to a number of the issues and concerns in plastic waste disposal and recycling.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Plastics pose a particular challenge in recycling because they are derived from polymers and monomers that often cannot be separated and returned to their virgin states.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] For this reason not all plastics can be recycled for re-use, in fact some estimates claim only 20–30% of plastics can be recycled at all.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Fibre-reinforced plastics and their matrices share these disposal and environmental concerns.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In addition to concerns regarding safe disposal, the fact that the fibres themselves are difficult to remove from the matrix and preserve for re-use means FRP's amplify these challenges.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] FRP's are inherently difficult to separate into base materials, that is into fibre and matrix, and the matrix is difficult to separate into usable plastics, polymers, and monomers.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] These are all concerns for environmentally-informed design today.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] Plastics do often offer savings in energy and economic savings in comparison to other materials.
[src:composite-materials/fiber-reinforced-plastic] In addition, with the advent of new more environmentally friendly matrices such as bioplastics and UV-degradable plastics, FRP will gain environmental sensitivity.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Cheaper and more flexible than carbon fiber, it is stronger than many metals by weight, non-magnetic, non-conductive, transparent to electromagnetic radiation, can be molded into complex shapes, and is chemically inert under many circumstances.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Applications include aircraft, boats, automobiles, bath tubs and enclosures, swimming pools, hot tubs, septic tanks, water tanks, roofing, pipes, cladding, orthopedic casts, surfboards, and external door skins.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Other common names for fiberglass are **glass-reinforced plastic** (**GRP**), **glass-fiber reinforced plastic** (**GFRP**) or **GFK** (from German: *Glasfaserverstärkter Kunststoff*).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Because glass fiber itself is sometimes referred to as "fiberglass", the composite is also called **fiberglass-reinforced plastic** (**FRP**).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] This article uses "fiberglass" to refer to the complete fiber-reinforced composite material, rather than only to the glass fiber within it.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Glass fibers have been produced for centuries, but the earliest patent was awarded to the Prussian inventor Hermann Hammesfahr (1845–1914) in the U.S. in 1880.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Mass production of glass strands was accidentally discovered in 1932 when Games Slayter, a researcher at Owens-Illinois, directed a jet of compressed air at a stream of molten glass and produced fibers.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Owens joined with the Corning company in 1935 and the method was adapted by Owens Corning to produce its patented "Fiberglas" (spelled with one "s") in 1936.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Originally, Fiberglas was a glass wool with fibers entrapping a great deal of gas, making it useful as an insulator, especially at high temperatures.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] A suitable resin for combining the fiberglass with a plastic to produce a composite material was developed in 1936 by DuPont.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] With the combination of fiberglass and resin the gas content of the material was replaced by plastic.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] This reduced the insulation properties to values typical of the plastic, but now for the first time, the composite showed great strength and promise as a structural and building material.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Many glass fiber composites continued to be called "fiberglass" (as a generic name) and the name was also used for the low-density glass wool product containing gas instead of plastic.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Ray Greene of Owens Corning is credited with producing the first composite boat in 1937 but did not proceed further at the time because of the brittle nature of the plastic used.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In 1939 the Soviet Union was reported to have constructed a passenger boat of plastic materials, and the United States a fuselage and wings of an aircraft.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The first car to have a fiberglass body was a 1946 prototype of the Stout Scarab, but the model did not enter production.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Unlike glass fibers used for insulation, strong structural fiber surfaces must be almost entirely free of defects in order to reach gigapascal tensile strengths.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] If a bulk piece of glass were defect-free, it would be as strong as glass fibers; however, it is generally impractical to produce and maintain bulk material in a defect-free state outside of laboratory conditions.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The process of manufacturing fiberglass is called pultrusion.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The manufacturing process for glass fibers suitable for reinforcement uses large furnaces to gradually melt the silica sand, limestone, kaolin, fluorspar, colemanite, dolomite and other minerals until a liquid forms.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] It is then extruded through bushings (spinneret), which are bundles of very small orifices (typically 5–25 micrometers in diameter for E-Glass, 9 micrometers for S-Glass).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] These filaments are then *sized* (coated) with a chemical solution.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The individual filaments are now bundled in large numbers to provide a roving.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Chopped strand mat (CSM) is a form of reinforcement used in fiberglass.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] It consists of glass fibers laid randomly across each other and held together by a binder.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] It is typically processed using the hand lay-up technique, where sheets of material are placed on a mold and brushed with resin.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Because the binder dissolves in resin, the material easily conforms to different shapes when wetted out.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] After the resin cures, the hardened product can be taken from the mold and finished.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Using chopped strand mat gives the fiberglass isotropic in-plane material properties.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] A coating or primer is applied to the roving to help protect the glass filaments for processing and manipulation and to ensure proper bonding to the resin matrix, thus allowing for the transfer of shear loads from the glass fibers to the thermoset plastic.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Without this bonding, the fibers can 'slip' in the matrix causing localized failure.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] An individual structural glass fiber is both stiff and strong in tension and compression—that is, *along* its axis.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Although it might be assumed that the fiber is weak in compression, it is actually only the long aspect ratio of the fiber which makes it seem so; i.e., because a typical fiber is long and narrow, it buckles easily.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] On the other hand, the glass fiber is weak in shear—that is, *across* its axis.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Therefore, if a collection of fibers can be arranged permanently in a preferred direction within a material, and if they can be prevented from buckling in compression, the material will be preferentially strong in that direction.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Furthermore, by laying multiple layers of fiber on top of one another, with each layer oriented in various preferred directions, the material's overall stiffness and strength can be efficiently controlled.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In fiberglass, it is the plastic matrix which permanently constrains the structural glass fibers to directions chosen by the designer.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] With chopped strand mat, this directionality is essentially an entire two-dimensional plane; with woven fabrics or unidirectional layers, directionality of stiffness and strength can be more precisely controlled within the plane.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] A fiberglass component is typically of a thin "shell" construction, sometimes filled on the inside with structural foam, as in the case of surfboards.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The component may be of nearly arbitrary shape, limited only by the complexity and tolerances of the mold used for manufacturing the shell.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The mechanical functionality of materials is heavily reliant on the combined performances of both the resin (AKA matrix) and fibers.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] For example, in severe temperature conditions (over 180 °C), the resin component of the composite may lose its functionality, partially due to bond deterioration of resin and fiber.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] However, GFRPs can still show significant residual strength after experiencing high temperatures (200 °C).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] One notable feature of fiberglass is that the resins used are subject to contraction during the curing process.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] For polyester this contraction is often 5–6%; for epoxy, about 2%.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Because the fibers do not contract, this differential can create changes in the shape of the part during curing.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Distortions can appear hours, days, or weeks after the resin has set.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] While this distortion can be minimized by symmetric use of the fibers in the design, a certain amount of internal stress is created; and if it becomes too great, cracks form.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The most common types of glass fiber used in fiberglass is E-glass, which is alumino-borosilicate glass with less than 1% w/w alkali oxides, mainly used for glass-reinforced plastics.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Pure silica (silicon dioxide), when cooled as fused quartz into a glass with no true melting point, can be used as a glass fiber for fiberglass but has the drawback that it must be worked at very high temperatures.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In order to lower the necessary work temperature, other materials are introduced as "fluxing agents" (i.e., components to lower the melting point).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Ordinary A-glass ("A" for "alkali-lime") or soda lime glass, crushed and ready to be remelted, as so-called cullet glass, was the first type of glass used for fiberglass.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] E-glass ("E" because of initial Electrical application), is alkali-free and was the first glass formulation used for continuous filament formation.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] It now makes up most of the fiberglass production in the world, and also is the single largest consumer of boron minerals globally.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] It is susceptible to chloride ion attack and is a poor choice for marine applications.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] S-glass ("S" for "stiff") is used when tensile strength (high modulus) is important and is thus an important building and aircraft epoxy composite (it is called R-glass, "R" for "reinforcement" in Europe).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] C-glass ("C" for "chemical resistance") and T-glass ("T" is for "thermal insulator"—a North American variant of C-glass) are resistant to chemical attack; both are often found in insulation-grades of blown fiberglass.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Fiberglass is versatile because it is lightweight, strong, weather-resistant, and can have a variety of surface textures.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] During World War II, fiberglass was developed as a replacement for the molded plywood used in aircraft radomes (fiberglass being transparent to microwaves).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Its first main civilian application was for the building of boats and sports car bodies, where it gained acceptance in the 1950s.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Its use has broadened to the automotive and sport equipment sectors.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In the production of some products, such as aircraft, carbon fiber is now used instead of fiberglass, which is stronger by volume and weight.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Advanced manufacturing techniques such as pre-pregs and fiber rovings extend fiberglass's applications and the tensile strength possible with fiber-reinforced plastics.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Fiberglass is also used in the telecommunications industry for shrouding antennas, due to its RF permeability and low signal attenuation properties.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] It may also be used to conceal other equipment where no signal permeability is required, such as equipment cabinets and steel support structures, due to the ease with which it can be molded and painted to blend with existing structures and surfaces.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Other uses include sheet-form electrical insulators and structural components commonly found in power-industry products.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Because of fiberglass's lightweight and durability, it is often used in protective equipment such as helmets.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Many sports use fiberglass protective gear, such as goaltenders' and catchers' masks.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Storage tanks can be made of fiberglass with capacities up to about 300 tonnes.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Smaller tanks can be made with chopped strand mat cast over a thermoplastic inner tank which acts as a preform during construction.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Much more reliable tanks are made using woven mat or filament wound fiber, with the fiber orientation at right angles to the hoop stress imposed in the sidewall by the contents.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Such tanks tend to be used for chemical storage because the plastic liner (often polypropylene) is resistant to a wide range of corrosive chemicals.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Fiberglass is also used for septic tanks.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Glass-reinforced plastics are also used to produce house building components such as roofing laminate, door surrounds, over-door canopies, window canopies and dormers, chimneys, coping systems, and heads with keystones and sills.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The material's reduced weight and easier handling, compared to wood or metal, allows faster installation.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Mass-produced fiberglass brick-effect panels can be used in the construction of composite housing, and can include insulation to reduce heat loss.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In rod pumping applications, fiberglass rods are often used for their high tensile strength to weight ratio.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Fiberglass rods provide an advantage over steel rods because they stretch more elastically (lower Young's modulus) than steel for a given weight, meaning more oil can be lifted from the hydrocarbon reservoir to the surface with each stroke, all while reducing the load on the pumping unit.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Fiberglass rods must be kept in tension, however, as they frequently part if placed in even a small amount of compression.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The buoyancy of the rods within a fluid amplifies this tendency.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Fiberglass composite boats have been made since the early 1940s, and many sailing vessels made after 1950 were built using the fiberglass lay-up process.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] As of 2022, boats continue to be made with fiberglass, though more advanced techniques such as vacuum bag moulding are used in the construction process.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Though most bullet-resistant armours are made using different textiles, fiberglass composites have been shown to be effective as ballistic armor.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Filament winding is a fabrication technique mainly used for manufacturing open (cylinders) or closed-end structures (pressure vessels or tanks).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The process involves winding filaments under tension over a male mandrel.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The mandrel rotates while a wind eye on a carriage moves horizontally, laying down fibers in the desired pattern.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The most common filaments are carbon or glass fiber and are coated with synthetic resin as they are wound.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Once the mandrel is completely covered to the desired thickness, the resin is cured; often the mandrel is placed in an oven to achieve this, though sometimes radiant heaters are used with the mandrel still turning in the machine.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Once the resin has cured, the mandrel is removed, leaving the hollow final product.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] For some products such as gas bottles, the 'mandrel' is a permanent part of the finished product forming a liner to prevent gas leakage or as a barrier to protect the composite from the fluid to be stored.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Filament winding is well suited to automation, and there are many applications, such as pipe and small pressure vessels that are wound and cured without any human intervention.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The controlled variables for winding are fiber type, resin content, wind angle, tow or bandwidth and thickness of the fiber bundle.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The angle at which the fiber has an effect on the properties of the final product.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] A high angle "hoop" will provide circumferential or "burst" strength, while lower angle patterns (polar or helical) will provide greater longitudinal tensile strength.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Products currently being produced using this technique range from pipes, golf clubs, Reverse Osmosis Membrane Housings, oars, bicycle forks, bicycle rims, power and transmission poles, pressure vessels to missile casings, aircraft fuselages and lamp posts and yacht masts.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] A release agent, usually in either wax or liquid form, is applied to the chosen mold to allow the finished product to be cleanly removed from the mold.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Resin—typically a 2-part thermoset polyester, vinyl, or epoxy—is mixed with its hardener and applied to the surface.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Sheets of fiberglass matting are laid into the mold, then more resin mixture is added using a brush or roller.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The material must conform to the mold, and air must not be trapped between the fiberglass and the mold.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Additional resin is applied and possibly additional sheets of fiberglass.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Hand pressure, vacuum or rollers are used to be sure the resin saturates and fully wets all layers, and that any air pockets are removed.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The work must be done quickly before the resin starts to cure unless high-temperature resins are used which will not cure until the part is warmed in an oven.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In some cases, the work is covered with plastic sheets and vacuum is drawn on the work to remove air bubbles and press the fiberglass to the shape of the mold.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The fiberglass spray lay-up process is similar to the hand lay-up process but differs in the application of the fiber and resin to the mold.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Spray-up is an open-molding composites fabrication process where resin and reinforcements are sprayed onto a mold.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The resin and glass may be applied separately or simultaneously "chopped" in a combined stream from a chopper gun.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Workers roll out the spray-up to compact the laminate.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Wood, foam or other core material may then be added, and a secondary spray-up layer imbeds the core between the laminates.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The part is then cured, cooled, and removed from the reusable mold.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Pultrusion is a manufacturing method used to make strong, lightweight composite materials.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In pultrusion, material is pulled through forming machinery using either a hand-over-hand method or a continuous-roller method (as opposed to extrusion, where the material is pushed through dies).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In fiberglass pultrusion, fibers (the glass material) are pulled from spools through a device that coats them with a resin.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] They are then typically heat-treated and cut to length.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Fiberglass produced this way can be made in a variety of shapes and cross-sections, such as W or S cross-sections.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] People can be exposed to fiberglass in the workplace during its fabrication, installation or removal, by breathing it in, by skin contact, or by eye contact.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Furthermore, in the manufacturing process of fiberglass, styrene vapors are released while the resins are cured.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] These are also irritating to mucous membranes and respiratory tract.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The general population can get exposed to fiberglass from insulation and building materials or from fibers in the air near manufacturing facilities or when they are near building fires or implosions.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The American Lung Association advises that fiberglass insulation should never be left exposed in an occupied area.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Since work practices are not always followed, and fiberglass is often left exposed in basements that later become occupied, people can get exposed.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] No readily usable biological or clinical indices of exposure exist.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Fiberglass will irritate the eyes, skin, and the respiratory system.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Hence, symptoms can include itchy eyes, skin, nose, sore throat, hoarseness, dyspnea (breathing difficulty) and cough.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Peak alveolar deposition was observed in rodents and humans for fibers with diameters of 1 to 2 μm.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In animal experiments, adverse lung effects such as lung inflammation and lung fibrosis have occurred, and increased incidences of mesothelioma, pleural sarcoma, and lung carcinoma had been found with intrapleural or intratracheal instillations in rats.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The more commonly used glass fiere wools including insulation glass wool, rock wool and slag wool are considered not classifiable as to carcinogenicity to humans (IARC Group 3).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In October 2001, all fiberglass wools commonly used for thermal and acoustical insulation were reclassified by the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) as "not classifiable as to carcinogenicity to humans" (IARC group 3).
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] However, NTP still considers fibrous glass dust to be "reasonably anticipated [as] a human carcinogen (Certain Glass Wool Fibers (Inhalable))".
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] As of 2012, the North American Insulation Manufacturers Association stated that fiberglass is safe to manufacture, install and use when recommended work practices are followed to reduce temporary mechanical irritation.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] As of 2012, the European Union and Germany have classified synthetic glass fibers as possibly or probably carcinogenic, but fibers can be exempt from this classification if they pass specific tests.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Genetic and toxic effects are exerted through production of reactive oxygen species, which can damage DNA, and cause chromosomal aberrations, nuclear abnormalities, mutations, gene amplification in proto-oncogenes, and cell transformation in mammalian cells.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] There is also indirect, inflammation-driven genotoxicity through reactive oxygen species by inflammatory cells.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The longer and thinner as well as the more durable (biopersistent) fibers were, the more potent they were in damage.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) has set a recommended exposure limit (REL) of 3 fibers/cm3 (less than 3.5 micrometers in diameter and greater than 10 micrometers in length) as a time-weighted average over an 8-hour workday, and a 5 mg/m3 total limit.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] As of 2001, the Hazardous Substances Ordinance in Germany dictates a maximum occupational exposure limit of 86 mg/m3.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] In certain concentrations, a potentially explosive mixture may occur.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] Further manufacture of GRP components (grinding, cutting, sawing) creates fine dust and chips containing glass filaments, as well as tacky dust, in quantities high enough to affect health and the functionality of machines and equipment.
[src:composite-materials/fiberglass] The installation of effective extraction and filtration equipment is required to ensure safety and efficiency.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Lamination may be applied to textiles, glass, wood, or other materials.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Laminating paper in plastic makes it sturdy, waterproof, and erasable.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Laminating metals and electronic components may provide electrical insulation and other benefits.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] There are different lamination processes, depending primarily on the type or types of materials to be laminated.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The materials used in laminates can be identical or different, depending on the object to be laminated, the process and the desired properties.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Laminated fabric are widely used in different fields of human activity, including medical and military.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Coated fabrics may be considered as a subtype of laminated fabrics.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Nonwoven fabrics (e.g. fiberglass) are also often laminated.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] According to a 2002 source, the nonwovens fabric industry was the biggest single consumer of different polymer binding resins.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Materials used in production of coated and laminated fabrics are generally subjected to heat treatment.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Thermoplastics and thermosetting plastics (e.g. formaldehyde polymers) are equally used in laminating and coating textile industry.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] In 2002 primary materials used included polyvinyl acetate, acrylics, polyvinyl chloride (PVC), polyurethanes, and natural and synthetic rubbers.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Copolymers and terpolymers were also in use.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Thin-films of plastics were in wide use as well.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Materials varied from polyethylene and PVC to kapton depending on application.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] In automotive industry for example the PVC/acrylonitrilebutadiene-styrene (ABS) mixtures were often applied for interiors by laminating onto a polyurethane foam to give a soft-touch properties.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Specialty films were used in protective clothing, .e.g. polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE), polyurethane etc.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Plastic film can be used to laminate either side of a sheet of glass.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Vehicle windshields are commonly made as composites created by laminating a tough plastic film between two layers of glass.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] This is to prevent shards of glass detaching from the windshield in case it breaks.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Plywood is a common example of a laminate using the same material in each layer combined with an adhesive.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Glued and laminated dimensional timber is used in the construction industry to make beams (glued laminated timber, or *Glulam*), in sizes larger and stronger than those that can be obtained from single pieces of wood.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Another reason to laminate wooden strips into beams is quality control, as with this method each and every strip can be inspected before it becomes part of a highly stressed component.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Examples of laminate materials include melamine adhesive countertop surfacing and plywood.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Decorative laminates and some modern millwork components are produced with decorative papers with a layer of overlay on top of the decorative paper, set before pressing them with thermoprocessing into high-pressure decorative laminates (HPDL).
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A new type of HPDL is produced using real wood veneer or multilaminar veneer as top surface.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] High-pressure laminates consists of laminates "molded and cured at pressures not lower than 1,000 lb per sq in.(70 kg per cm2) and more commonly in the range of 1,200 to 2,000 lb per sq in.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Meanwhile, low pressure laminate is defined as "a plastic laminate molded and cured at pressures in general of 400 pounds per square inch (approximately 27 atmospheres or 2.8 × 106 pascals).
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Corrugated fiberboard boxes are examples of laminated structures, where an inner core provides rigidity and strength, and the outer layers provide a smooth surface.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A starch-based adhesive is usually used.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Laminating paper (including coated paper such as glossy, matte, or soft-touch finishes) products, such as photographs, can prevent them from becoming creased, faded, water damaged, wrinkled, stained, smudged, abraded, or marked by grease or fingerprints.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Photo identification cards and credit cards are almost always laminated with plastic film.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Boxes and other containers may be laminated using heat seal layers, extrusion coatings, pressure sensitive adhesives, UV coating, etc.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Gloss lamination provides a "shiny" finish that can make colors appear more vibrant, while matte lamination offers a non-reflective surface that helps reduce glare.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A "soft-touch" laminate can be applied as a thin polymer film to give a "velvety" tactile feel while adding a protective layer.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Lamination is also used in sculpture using wood or resin.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] An example of an artist who used lamination in his work is the American Floyd Shaman.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Laminates can be used to add properties to a surface, usually printed paper, that would not have them otherwise, such as with the use of lamination paper.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Sheets of vinyl impregnated with ferro-magnetic material can allow portable printed images to bond to magnets, such as for a custom bulletin board or a visual presentation.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Specially surfaced plastic sheets can be laminated over a printed image to allow them to be safely written upon, such as with dry erase markers or chalk.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Multiple translucent printed images may be laminated in layers to achieve certain visual effects or to hold holographic images.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Printing businesses that do commercial lamination keep a variety of laminates on hand, as the process for bonding different types is generally similar when working with thin materials.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Paper is normally laminated on particle or fiberboards giving a good-looking and resistant surface for use as furniture, decoration panels and flooring.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Paper laminations are also used in packaging.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] For example, juiceboxes are fabricated from liquid packaging board which is usually six layers of paper, polyethylene, and aluminum foil.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Paper is used in the lamination to shape the product and give the juicebox an extra source of strength.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The base is most often particle- or fiberboards, then some layers of absorbent kraft paper.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The last layers are a *decor paper* covered with an *overlay*.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The lamination papers are covered with an inert resin, often melamine, which is cured to form a hard composite with the structure of paper.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The laminates may also have a lining on the back side of *laminating kraft* to compensate for the tension created by the top side lamination.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Cheaper particle boards may have only a lining of laminating kraft to give surface washability and resistance to wear.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The *decor paper* can also be processed under heat and low/high pressure to create a melamine laminated sheet, that has several applications.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The absorbent kraft paper is a normal kraft paper with controlled absorbency, which means a high degree of porosity.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] It is made of clean low kappa hardwood kraft with good uniformity.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The grammage is 80 - 120 g/m2 and normally 2-4 plies are used.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The decor paper is the most critical of the lamination papers as it gives the visual appearance of the laminate.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The impregnation resin and cellulose have about the same refraction index which means that the cellulose fibers of the paper appear as a shade and only the dyestuffs and pigments are visible.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Due to this the decor paper demands extreme cleanness and is produced only on small paper machines with grammage 50 - 150 g/m2.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The overlay paper have grammage of 18 – 50 m2 and is made of pure cellulose, thus it must be made of well delignified pulp.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] It becomes transparent after impregnation letting the appearance of the decor paper come through.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The laminating kraft have a grammage of 70 - 150 g/m2 and is a smooth dense kraft paper.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Electrical equipment such as transformers and motors usually use an electrical steel laminate coatings to form the core of the coils used to produce magnetic fields.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The thin lamination reduces the power loss due to eddy currents.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Fiber metal laminate is an example of thin metal laminated by, a glass fiber-reinforced and epoxy-glued sheets.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Lamination is widely used in production of electronic components such as PV solar cells.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A **laminator** is a device which laminates pieces or rolls of paper or card stock, common in offices, schools, and homes.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A pouch laminator uses a plastic pouch that is usually sealed on one edge.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The inside of the lamination pouch is coated with a heat-activated film that adheres to the product being laminated as it runs through the laminator.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The substrate side of the board contains a heat-activated adhesive that bonds the print to the substrate.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] This can be any of a number of board products or another sheet of laminate.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The pouch containing the print, laminate, and substrate is passed through a set of heated rollers under pressure, ensuring that all adhesive layers bond to one another.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Pouch laminators are designed for moderate use in the office or home.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] For continuous, large-volume lamination projects, a roll laminator performs more efficiently.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Pouches can be bought with different thicknesses in micrometres.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Standard home or office machines normally use 80–250 micrometre pouches, depending on the quality of the machine.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The thicker the pouch, the higher the cost.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Pouches can also measured in mil, which equals one thousandth of an inch.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The most common pouch thicknesses are 3, 5, 7 and 10 mil (76, 127, 178 and 254 μm).
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Certain pouches such as butterfly pouches can be used with a pouch laminator to form ID cards.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Butterfly pouches are available with magnetic stripes embedded.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Many pouch laminators require the use of a carrier.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A carrier holds the pouch as it is run through the laminator.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] This helps prevent the hot glue, some of which leaks from the sides of the pouches during the process, from gumming up the rollers.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The carrier prevents the rollers from getting sticky, which helps to prevent the lamination pouch from wrapping around the rollers inside the laminator.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Many newer laminators claim that they can be used without a carrier.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] However the use of carriers will extend the laminator's life.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A heated roll laminator uses heated rollers to melt glue extruded onto lamination film.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] This film is in turn applied to a substrate such as paper or card using pressure rollers.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The primary purpose of laminating with such a machine is to embellish or protect printed documents or images.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Heated roll laminators can vary in size from handheld or desktop pouch laminators to industrial sized machines.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Such industrial laminators are primarily used for high quantity/quality output by printers or print finishers.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Such laminators are used to apply varying thicknesses of lamination film onto substrates such as paper or fabrics.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The main advantage of the use of heated roll laminators is speed.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Heated laminators use heated rollers or heated shoes to melt the glue which is applied to lamination film.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The process of heating the glue prior to applying the film to a substrate allows for a faster application of the film.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The laminates and adhesives used are generally cheaper to manufacture than cold roll laminates, often as much as half the cost depending on the comparison made.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] As the materials are non-adhesive until exposed to heat, they are much easier to handle.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The glue is solid at room temperature, so lamination of this type is less likely to shift or warp after its application than pressure activated laminates, which rely on a highly viscous, adhesive fluid.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Roll laminators typically use two rolls to complete the lamination process, with one roll being on top and the other roll on the bottom.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] These rolls slide onto metal bars, known as mandrels, which are then placed in the machine and feed through it.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] In the United States, the most common core size found on lamination film is one inch (25- to 27-inch-wide film).
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Larger format laminators use a larger core, often 21⁄4 to 3 inches in diameter.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Film is usually available in 1.5, 3, 5, 7, and 10 mil thicknesses.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] The higher the number, the thicker the film.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A mil is one thousandth of an inch (.001").
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Printers or print finishers often use industrial heated roll laminators to laminate such things as paperback book covers, magazine covers, posters, business cards, presentation folders, and postcards, in-shop displays as well as other applications.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Cold roll laminators use a plastic film which is coated with an adhesive and glossy backing which does not adhere to the glue.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] When the glossy backing is removed, the adhesive is exposed, which then sticks directly onto the item which needs to be laminated.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] This method, apart from having the obvious benefit of not requiring expensive equipment, is also suitable for those items which would be damaged by heat.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Cold laminators range from simple two roller, hand-crank machines up to large and complex motor-driven machines with high precision rollers, adjustable roller pressure, and other advanced features.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Cold lamination increased in popularity with the rise of wide-format inkjet printers, which often used inks and papers incompatible with hot lamination.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A large percentage of cold laminate for use in the print industry is PVC, although a wide range of other materials are available.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Cold laminating processes are also used outside of the print industry, for example, coating sheet glass or stainless steel with protective films.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] Cold roll laminators are also used for laying down adhesive films in the sign-making industry, for example mounting a large print onto a board.
[src:composite-materials/laminate] A practiced operator can apply a large adhesive sheet in a fraction of the time it takes to do so by hand.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] In materials science, a **matrix** is a constituent of a composite material.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Traditional materials such as glues, muds have traditionally been used as matrices for adobe and papier-mâché.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] The common matrices are polymers (mainly utilized for fibre reinforced plastics).
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] The most common polymer-based composite materials which include carbon fibre, fibreglass and Kevlar, typically involve two parts at least, the resin and the substrate.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Asphalt concrete, which is often used in the construction of roads, has a matrix called bitumen.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Mud (wattle and daub) has observed considerable use.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Epoxy is utilized as a structural glue or structural matrix material in the aerospace industry.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Epoxy resin is, when cured, nearly transparent.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Polyester resin is fit for most backyard projects.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] It is often used in the construction of surfboards and for marine applications.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] They are usually coated as they can tend to deteriorate over time and sensitive to ultraviolet.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Peroxide is considered as the hardener of polyester resin.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Mostly, MEKP (methyl ethyl ketone peroxide) is considered for polyester resin.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] A curing reaction is initiated when the peroxide is combined with the resin, and decomposes to generate free radicals.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] In these systems, often hardeners are called catalysts.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] But they do not meet the strictest chemical definition of a catalyst as at the end of the reaction they do not re-appear unchanged.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Vinyl ester resin has a lower viscosity than polyester resin and is more transparent.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] It also tends to have a purplish to bluish to greenish tint.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] The price of the vinyl ester resin is similar to that of the polyester resin.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] It utilizes the same hardeners as polyester resin (at a similar mix ratio).
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] It doesn't degrade much over time, when compared to polyester resin, and is more flexible.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Generally, vinyl ester resin is considered as fuel resistant.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] However, it will melt when in contact with gasoline.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Shape memory polymer (SMP) resins are those materials that their shape and can be modified regularly by heating above their glass transition temperature (T*g*).
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] They become elastic and flexible when heated, allowing for easy configuration.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] They maintain their new shape when they are cooled.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] When they are reheated above their T*g,* they will return to their original shape.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] The benefit of these resins is that without losing their material properties, they can be shaped and reshaped regularly.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] These resins can be utilized in making shape memory composites.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Depending on their formulation, they have varying visual characteristics.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Cement (concrete), ceramics, sometimes glasses and metals are employed.
[src:composite-materials/matrix-composite] Unusual matrices such as ice are sometimes proposed as in pykecrete.
